  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "Fc+UfB+f5eGQaz8kYVY8/lYlBIc=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:40.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "## Claim\nReactor sync state is durable across sessions because it lives in four dedicated PGlite tables.\n\n## Tables (from source)\n| Table | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `sync_remotes` | Registered remotes: name, collection_id, channel_type, push/pull state |\n| `sync_cursors` | Per-remote cursor tracking: ordinal position (inbox & outbox) |\n| `sync_dead_letters` | Failed operations with error details |\n| `operation_index_operations` | Global ordinal index across all operations |\n\n## Why this matters\n- Swarm remotes registered via `syncManager.add(...)` persist in `sync_remotes` and are recreated natively on startup \u2014 no re-registration code needed after reload.\n- Cursors in `sync_cursors` provide exactly-once push semantics: the outbox cursor advances only after a successful remote write.\n- `operation_index_operations` is the shared global ordinal space that lets multiple remotes coexist without stepping on each other.\n\n## Source\nSwarm Channel Architecture, \"PGlite Tables\" table.",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:40.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:40.000Z"
    }
  },
